- name: Troubleshooting Parallel Mode
  id: index#troubleshooting-parallel-mode
  summary: null
  description: |-
    ### Troubleshooting Parallel Mode

    If you find your tests don‚Äôt work properly when run with [`--parallel`](#-parallel-p), either shrug and move on, or use this handy-dandy checklist to get things working:

    - ‚úÖ Ensure you are using a [supported reporter](#reporter-limitations).
    - ‚úÖ Ensure you are not using [other unsupported flags](#file-order-is-non-deterministic).
    - ‚úÖ Double-check your [config file](#configuring-mocha-nodejs); options set in config files will be merged with any command-line option.
    - ‚úÖ Look for root hooks (they look like [this](#root-hooks-are-not-global)) in your tests. Move them into a [Root Hook Plugin](#root-hook-plugins).
    - ‚úÖ Do any assertion, mock, or other test libraries you‚Äôre consuming use root hooks? They may need to be [migrated](#migrating-a-library-to-use-root-hook-plugins) for compatibility with parallel mode.
    - ‚úÖ If tests are unexpectedly timing out, you may need to increase the default test timeout (via [`--timeout`](#-timeout-ms-t-ms))
    - ‚úÖ Ensure your tests do not depend on being run in a specific order.
    - ‚úÖ Ensure your tests clean up after themselves; remove temp files, handles, sockets, etc. Don‚Äôt try to share state or resources between test files.

    &nbsp;
- name: Using async / await
  id: index#using-async-await
  summary: null
  description: |-
    ### Using async / await

    If your JS environment supports [async / await](https://developer.mozilla.org/en/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/async_function), you can also write asynchronous tests like this:

    ``` javascript
    beforeEach(async function() {
      await db.clear();
      await db.save([tobi, loki, jane]);
    });

    describe('#find()', function() {
      it('responds with matching records', async function() {
        const users = await db.find({type: 'User'});
        users.should.have.length(3);
      });
    });
    ```
